# Object Detection - Head Characteristics & NMS

## Overview
Non-Maximum Suppression (NMS) variations based on detection head characteristics.

## Key Concepts
- Each detection head (classification, regression, objectness) has different characteristics
- NMS strategy should adapt based on head behavior and confidence distributions
- Some heads don't need traditional NMS (e.g., anchor-free, center-based approaches)

## NMS-Free / NMS-Variant Heads

### 1. **Anchor-Free / Center-Based**
- FCOS, CenterNet, FCOS-TRUNK
- Use center distance/penalty instead of overlap-based NMS
- Single peak per object naturally

### 2. **DETR-style (Transformer)**
- Deformable DETR, DINO, DN-DETR
- Set-based prediction with bipartite matching
- No post-processing NMS needed - one prediction per class

### 3. **FCOS + CornerNet**
- Corner detection based
- Pairing instead of overlap suppression
- Use distance thresholds

### 4. **YOLO variants with Objectness**
- YOLOv7, YOLOv8, YOLOv9
- Objectness score reduces false positives
- Can use soft-NMS or variant approaches

## NMS Strategies by Head Type

| Head Type | Traditional NMS | Soft-NMS | DIoU-NMS | Panoptic NMS |
|-----------|----------------|----------|----------|--------------|
| Anchor-based (SSD) | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | - |
| Anchor-free (FCOS) | - | ✓ | ✓ | - |
| Transformer (DETR) | ✗ | ✗ | ✗ | ✓ |
| Corner-based | - | - | ✓ | - |
| Centroid-based | - | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |

## Notes

### When NMS is not needed:
1. **Per-class max pooling**: If head produces single max per class
2. **Set prediction**: Transformer approaches with Hungarian matching
3. **Center-based**: When center points are distinct

### When to use variant NMS:
1. **Occlusion cases**: Soft-NMS or weighted averaging
2. **Tightly packed objects**: DIoU-NMS, SIoU-NMS
3. **Different scale objects**: Multi-level NMS
4. **Pose/Keypoint heads**: Joint constraints instead of NMS

